<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#case_MPX1433">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#Case"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1433_synpic52647"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1433_synpic52648"/>
  <hasPatient rdf:resource="#patient_0134"/>
  <title rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Dacryocystocele with dacryocystitis and periorbital cellulitis</title>
  <history rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A 4 month-old boy presents with left eye swelling for about 48hours that started with dark discoloration on left lower lid. No history of trauma.</history>
  <exam rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Afebrile. Left eye has periorbital swelling with palpable mass on medial canthus. No discharge.</exam>
  <finding rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A cystic mass located anteromedial to left globe</finding>
  <differential_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Dacryocystocele with or without dacryocystitis Periorbital cellulitis Orbital cellulitis Meningocele Encephalomeningocele Hemangioma Dermoid cyst Glioma</differential_diagnosis>
  <case_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Dacryocystocele with dacryocystitis and periorbital cellulitis</case_diagnosis>
  <diagnosis_by rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Head CT imaging</diagnosis_by>
  <discussion rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A dacryocystocele is a grey-blue cystic swelling often filled with mucoid material below the medial canthus. It is a rare complication of congenital nasolacrimal duct obstruction. It often results from incomplete canalization of the lower part of the nasolacrimal duct at the valve of Hasner (anatomical) and secondary obstruction proximally at the Rosenmuller valve from distension of the sac and compression of the canal system (functional). Incidence of imperforate NLD in full-term fetuses is 35-73% with spontaneous resolution in about 85-95% of patients by age 1. It is more common in females and often presents unilaterally. Complications include dacryocystitis, cellulitis, astigmatism, narrowing of lid fissure and respiratory difficulty from mass effect.</discussion>
  <treatment_follow_up rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Due to significant swelling around the eye, treatment for this patient included IV and topical antibiotics, probing, drainage and surgical marsupialization under general anesthesia.</treatment_follow_up>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

