<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#case_MPX1563">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#Case"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1563_synpic51033"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1563_synpic51034"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1563_synpic51035"/>
  <hasPatient rdf:resource="#patient_0167"/>
  <title rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Left frontal cavernous malformation with DVA.</title>
  <history rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">76 y.o. woman who fell; LOC; no trauma to head; twisted ankle</history>
  <exam rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Bruise on left ankle. No cranial nerve deficits or other neurological deficits.</exam>
  <finding rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">1.Outside head CT reported small 1cm homogenously round hyperdense lesion in left frontal lobe as an intraparenchymal hemorrhage (IPH).2.Head CT in our hospital 5 hours later: stable 1 cm homogenously round hyperdense lesion, suspicious for cavernoma, suggest MRI for confirmation. 3. Brain MRI later shows classic popcorn appearance on T2-weighted image with low T2 signal in the periphery of the lesion consistent with cavernoma. In addition, small deep frontal vessels, draining towards the left ventricle, are noted on the post-contrast T1W image, consistent with a developmental venous anomaly (DVA).</finding>
  <differential_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">1.IPH (intra-parenchymal hemorrhage)2.Other vascular lesions such as AVM, AVF, or aneurysm.3.Hypercellular neoplasm, either primary or metastatic.</differential_diagnosis>
  <case_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Left frontal cavernous malformation with DVA.</case_diagnosis>
  <diagnosis_by rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">MRI</diagnosis_by>
  <discussion rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Cavernomas are often associated with DVAs. Limited role of CT due to lack of specificity. MRI including T2 and GRE sequences are preferred. Ide C, De Coene B, Baudrez V. MR features of cavernous angioma. JBR-BTR. Dec 2000;83(6):320. Sage MR, Blumbergs PC. Cavernous haemangiomas (angiomas) of the brain. Australas Radiol. May 2001;45(2):247-56. Grossman RI, Yousem DM. Vascular diseases of the brain. In: Neuroradiology: The Requisites. St Louis: Mosby-Year Book;. 1994: 121-6, 141-2. Hallam DK, Russell EJ. Imaging of angiographically occult cerebral vascular malformations. Neuroimaging Clin N Am. May 1998;8(2):323-47.</discussion>
  <treatment_follow_up rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">1.No treatment if no symptoms. Can follow up over time.2.If symptomatic, stereotactic radiosurgery or surgery depending on individual cases.</treatment_follow_up>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

