<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#case_MPX1716">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#Case"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1716_synpic54798"/>
  <hasPatient rdf:resource="#patient_0211"/>
  <title rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Patent Ductus Arteriosus</title>
  <history rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">56 y.o. man, a commercial airline pilot, presented with with acute onset of severe chest pain, radiating to the back. PMH: HTN, HLP, Type B (descending aorta) thoracic aortic dissectionFamHx: noncontributoryMeds: Metoprolol, Amlodipine, HCTZ, Atorvastatin, OmeprazoleAllergies: NKDA</history>
  <exam rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Vital signs: 127/85 61bpm 68 206lb BMI 31.32CV: RRR, normal S1/S2. No murmurs. No carotid bruit. Normal peripheral pulses. No peripheral edema. EKG: Sinus bradycardia at 57bpm, otherwise normal.</exam>
  <finding rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Cardiac-gated CTA images in multiple planes demonstrate a patent ductus arteriosus, shown by a small contrast-enhanced vessel connecting the descending aorta to the pulmonary artery. Patency of vessel is demonstrated by a jet of contrast spilling into the pulmonary artery at its connection with the ductus arteriosus. Of note, you can see changes in the proximal descending aortic wall indicative of this patients stable aneurysm/dissection.</finding>
  <differential_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Patent ductus arteriosusIntraarterial fistula</differential_diagnosis>
  <case_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Patent Ductus Arteriosus</case_diagnosis>
  <diagnosis_by rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">CTA imaging is diagnostic.</diagnosis_by>
  <discussion rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Currently, this incidental finding of PDA is of little clinical consequence, as the patient does not have symptoms at this time. However, if he were to develop symptoms such as exercise intolerance or differential cyanosis, it would become important to evaluate the shunt fraction with a functional study or transthoracic echocardiogram.</discussion>
  <treatment_follow_up rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The plan for this patient is to follow his aortic dissection with cardiac-gated CT imaging at regular intervals. He is currently being managed with medication for blood pressure control, and the dissection has been stable over the intial 6 months since onset.Regarding the PDA, since it is long-standing and has at this point only caused mild dilation of the pulmonary artery, there is no plan to correct it. The patient has no symptoms from his PDA, either at rest or with exertion, and indeed no murmur is appreciable on exam.</treatment_follow_up>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#MPX1716_synpic54798">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#CT_Scan"/>
  <isScanOf rdf:resource="#case_MPX1716"/>
  <url rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">https://github.com/CHILab1/MedPix-2.0/blob/main/images/MPX1716_synpic54798.png</url>
  <caption rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Multiplanar reformat cardiac-gated CT aortic angiogram in the axial plane demonstrates a vessel with intra-arterial contrast projecting anteriorly from the descending aorta, distal to the takeoff of the left subclavian artery. There also appears to be a small amount of contrast within the adjacent pulmonary artery.</caption>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

