<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#case_MPX1793">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#Case"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1793_synpic41476"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1793_synpic41478"/>
  <hasPatient rdf:resource="#patient_0232"/>
  <title rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Granuloma</title>
  <history rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">10 y.o. girl with chronic congestion presented to clinic with new onset of cough and sore throat. The patient also had complained of 6 months of intermittent headaches. The patient denied any sputum production or fevers.</history>
  <exam rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Head: cloudy nasal dischargeLungs: scattered rhonchi, no crackles, no wheezingLymph: No cervical lymphadenopathyLABS: PPD negativeHistoplasma negativeESR 12WBC 9.3 (w/ NL distribution)</exam>
  <finding rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">There is a left upper lobe pulmonary nodule which measures approximately 1.1 cm in diameter. There is central calcification within this lesion, which has become slightly more dense over the year in between CT. The borders are well demarcated.</finding>
  <differential_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Granuloma -TB -HistoplasmosisHamartomaInfectious - Pneumocystis carinii -AspergillomaPulmonary metastatic disease Primary pulmonary malignancy</differential_diagnosis>
  <case_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Granuloma</case_diagnosis>
  <diagnosis_by rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Stability of lesion on follow up</diagnosis_by>
  <discussion rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">There are many algorithms for the evaluation of the solitary pulmonary nodule. In a young child, metastatic disease is very uncommon - and thus this girl was followed with repeat imaging that documented a stable lesion size - now, most likely a healed granuloma.</discussion>
  <treatment_follow_up rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">No further work up is necessary. It is important for the mother to convey these findings to future physicians when a chest xray or CT is performed and to relay the current dimensions.</treatment_follow_up>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

