<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#case_MPX1965">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#Case"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1965_synpic30982"/>
  <hasPatient rdf:resource="#patient_0274"/>
  <title rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Classical Hodgkins Lymphoma, nodular sclerosing type</title>
  <history rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">21 year old man with a 2 month history of abdominal pain, weight loss, fevers, and chills.</history>
  <exam rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">N/A</exam>
  <finding rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Increased densities in the anterior and posterior mediastinum Enlarged prevascular lymph node, 1.7cm Enlarged Peritracheal lymph node, 1.6cm Moderate pericardial effusion</finding>
  <differential_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Thymic tumors Pericardial tumors Mediastinal carcinoids Cystic mediastinal lesions Thoracic fungal infections Other causes of lymphadenopathy</differential_diagnosis>
  <case_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Classical Hodgkin's Lymphoma, nodular sclerosing type</case_diagnosis>
  <diagnosis_by rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">biopsy and histology</diagnosis_by>
  <discussion rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Lymphomas are divided into Hodgkins and non-Hodgkins. Hodgkins lymphoma is characterized by Reed-Sternberg cells, with 4 subtypes. In the thorax, nodular sclerosing is the most common subtype with a predilection for the mediastinum. Nodular sclerosing accounts for 50% of Hodgkins lymphomas. Frequency - In the US, 7400 estimated new cases in 2001 Bimodal distribution - 15-40 years old, 55 years old Treatment consists of radiation and/or chemotherapy Survival rates, 1yr-93%, 5yr-82%, 10yr-72%, 15yr-63%</discussion>
  <treatment_follow_up rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The Pt will receive combination radiation and chemotherapy. The overall 5 year survival for Hodgkins disease with treatment is 82%. PET scans are a useful means of staging and followup to determine relapse. This Pt has received a PET scan which will be entered and updated soon.</treatment_follow_up>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

