<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#case_MPX2224">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#Case"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX2224_synpic36031"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX2224_synpic36032"/>
  <hasPatient rdf:resource="#patient_0345"/>
  <title rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Bipartite Patella</title>
  <history rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">18 y/o man fell down the stairs. Now with right knee pain, localized to the patella. Pain is reported as constant and throbbing, increasing to 8-9/10 pain with weight bearing.</history>
  <exam rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Right knee with mild-moderate edema compared to left. Significant tenderness to palpation over entire knee, worse lateral to patella. Pt able to bear weight on right leg with difficulty.</exam>
  <finding rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Rounded bony fragment at superolateral aspect. Wide well-defined radiolucent line. Smooth, well-corticated, opposing margins. No sharp fracture fragments or intra-articular loose bodies. No evidence of suprapatellar effusion.</finding>
  <differential_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Bipartite patella, incidental Bipartite patella, symptomatic Patellar fracture Dorsal defect of the patella</differential_diagnosis>
  <case_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Bipartite Patella</case_diagnosis>
  <diagnosis_by rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Imaging</diagnosis_by>
  <discussion rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Bipartite patella (BP) is typically an incidental finding, with only 2% being symptomatic. Symptomatic BP is usually associated with chronic stress injury, although there are reported cases of symptomatic BP following injury. If the patient continues to have clinical tenderness over his superolateral pole for 3 months, surgery should be considered.</discussion>
  <treatment_follow_up rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">No treatment or follow-up required.</treatment_follow_up>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

