<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#case_MPX2359">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#Case"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX2359_synpic17942"/>
  <hasPatient rdf:resource="#patient_0400"/>
  <title rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Aortic Dissection</title>
  <history rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">76 year old gentleman with abdominal pain scheduled for a CT of the abdomen and pelvis to delineate cause.</history>
  <exam rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">PE: BP 160/93. Other vitals unremarkable.Labs: CBC, CHEM 7, AMYLASE/LIPASE, LFTs - WNL.</exam>
  <finding rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">- Infrarenal abdominal aorta (normal size) with a contrast-filled false lumen and displacement of intimal calcifications, between true and false lumens.</finding>
  <differential_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">- Aortic wall hematoma- Penetrating aortic ulcer- Chronic dissection</differential_diagnosis>
  <case_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Aortic Dissection</case_diagnosis>
  <treatment_follow_up rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">- When confined to the descending aorta (Stanford Type B) as this is, medical treatment is standard (control of HTN). Surgery is indicated if a Type B dissection is complicated by 1) an ischemic extremity, 2) mesenteric ischemia, 3) renal artery compromise, 4) rupture or 5) aneurysmal enlargement of false lumen.</treatment_follow_up>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#MPX2359_synpic17942">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#CT_Scan"/>
  <isScanOf rdf:resource="#case_MPX2359"/>
  <url rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">https://github.com/CHILab1/MedPix-2.0/blob/main/images/MPX2359_synpic17942.png</url>
  <caption rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Two select axial CT images through the mid-abdomen and specifically the infrarenal abdominal aorta demonstrate intraluminal displacement of the aortic intimal wall calcifications and a contrast-filled false lumen consistent with dissection.In this case, the false lumen is smaller and lateral to the true lumen. The bright dots are intimal calcifications displaced inward.</caption>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

