<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#case_MPX2607">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#Case"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX2607_synpic52587"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX2607_synpic52588"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX2607_synpic52590"/>
  <hasPatient rdf:resource="#patient_0485"/>
  <title rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Subependymoma, lateral ventricle</title>
  <history rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">44 yo man with headaches</history>
  <finding rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">There is a mass in the frontal horn of the right lateral ventricle. The lesion appears attached to medial, rather than the lateral wall.This lesion does not enhance after Gadolinium injection.</finding>
  <differential_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Ependymoma Subpendymoma Central Neurocytoma Choroid plexus neoplasm Choroid meningioma Choroid metastasis</differential_diagnosis>
  <case_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Subependymoma, lateral ventricle</case_diagnosis>
  <diagnosis_by rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Resection and histology</diagnosis_by>
  <discussion rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Subpendymomas are uncommon low-grade tumors, thought (perhaps) to arise from subependymal cells called tanycytes. These lesions occur most often either as asymptomatic masses in the 4th ventricle - or as symptomatic masses in the lateral ventricles.Most 4th ventricular ependymomas show some contrast enhancement; whereas most in the lateral ventricle do not enhance.</discussion>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

