<owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="#case_MPX1171">
  <rdf:type rdf:resource="#Case"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1171_synpic26485"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1171_synpic26486"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1171_synpic26487"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1171_synpic26497"/>
  <hasScan rdf:resource="#MPX1171_synpic26498"/>
  <hasPatient rdf:resource="#patient_0508"/>
  <title rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">1) Fronto-nasal encephalocele2) Colpocephaly</title>
  <history rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">2 day old female infant with midline mass above the nose.</history>
  <exam rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Soft midline mass noted above the patients nose.</exam>
  <finding rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">T1 sagital view showing enlarged posterior lateral ventricles. The image shows a midline opening of the skull above the bridge of the nose with protrusion of brain parenchyma through the skull defect.T2 axial views show bilateral asymmetrically enlarged lateral ventricles (rightleft). Brain parenchyma protruding from a midline skull defect at the level of the eyes with CSF communication into the mass. Parenchymal volume loss noted in parietal, occipital and frontal lobes.</finding>
  <differential_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">EncephaloceleMeningoceleGliomaHemangiomaNasal Dermoid</differential_diagnosis>
  <case_diagnosis rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">1) Fronto-nasal encephalocele
2) Colpocephaly</case_diagnosis>
  <diagnosis_by rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">MRI - protrusion of brain parenchyma and CSF through a midline skull defect is pathognomonic for encephalocele.</diagnosis_by>
  <discussion rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The open skull defect with protruding mass narrows the ddx to encephalocele and meningocele. Since both CSF and brain parenchyma are noted protruding from the skull defect, the dx is encephalocele.</discussion>
  <treatment_follow_up rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Treatment typically involves a frontal craniotomy with excision of the protruding and non-functional brain parenchyma. This requires immediate neurosurgical consultation. This particular patient is scheduled to undergo surgery.</treatment_follow_up>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

